Zeb'210 FPV Racer Quadcopter - custom frame. Presentation:
  • Inspired by Sigan's quadcopters design, but whole new design.
  • Designed for the list of parts here below.
  • All electronic parts are attached on the body (spacer) of the frame with specific mounts ; some adjustments might be necessary if you want to use different electronic parts.
  • The body and the two holders are intended to be printed in SLS nylon.
  • The three plates are intended to be cut from CFRP (3k carbon fiber sheet) 1.5mm thick sheets.
    • Specifications:
  • External dimensions are 217.5 x175.5 x46.5mm, with 213.3mm motor to motor, for 5" propellers.
  • The body is 15mm high (12mm inside space), and its external wall is 3mm thick.
  • The motors guards are 4mm thick, the motors mounts are tilted 12° forward and are 4mm thick.
  • The FPV camera is tilted 13° upward, and the camera lens guard is 2.5mm thick.
  • The Rx antennas are tilted 25° on each sides of the camera lens guard, which leaves 35mm clearance across the width for an external camera (Mobius for instance) on the top.
  • Accept battery up to 108mm long and 37mm wide, with suitable battery holder.
  • The battery holder is fixed on the middle plate using five oblong lugs.
  • The Mobius holder is fixed on top of the top plate, it protects the lens with a 2.5mm guard.
  • VTx channel setting is reachable from underneath with the frame closed.
  • USB ports from FC and OSD are both reachable from the left side with the frame closed.
  • FC's alarm buzzer mount leads the sound directly outside from the right side.
  • Three serial LEDs controlled by the FC are integrated in each arm for higher visibility.
    • Part list:
  • Flight Controller: RMRC Seriously Dodo rev3
  • PDB/OSD: MXK PDB with 5V and 12V converter, LC Filter, and minimOSD integrated
  • ESCs: FVT LittleBee 30A
  • Motors: Emax RS2205 2300kv
  • Props: HQprop 5045 Bullnose, HQprop 5040 Tri-blades and HQprop 5045 Bullnose Tri-blades
  • Camera: RunCam PZ0420M with 2.1mm lens
  • Action Camera: Mobius Wide Angle C2 with 32GB microSD card
  • Video Tx: Eachine ET600 with RP-SMA adapter and Fatshark SpiroNet
  • Remote Rx: Lemon RX PPM-8 Diversity LM0039 with Antenna mounts
  • LiPo: A few DroneLabs 4S 1800mAh 50~100C
  • Other: LEDs WS2812 Bandstripes, Battery Strap, Battery Pad, 5V Buzzer, XT60 connector, etc.
    • Needed hardware:
  • 1.5x450x200mm Carbon Fiber Sheet
  • 8x Hex Threaded Standoff M3x12mm
  • 4x Round Threaded Standoff M3x20mm
  • 24x Screw M3x6mm (for all Standoffs)
  • 8x Screw + Nut M3x6mm Nylon (for FC and PDB/OSD)
  • 6x Screw + Nut M2x6mm Nylon (for FPV Camera and XT60)
  • Small Zip Tie (for ESCs and Vtx)
  • Double-sided Adhesive (for Rx and LEDs)
    • Ground base:
  • Goggles: Quanum FPV Goggle V2
  • Video Rx: Eachine RC832
  • Remote Tx: Walkera DEVO 10 with DeviationTx firmware
  • LiPo: Turnigy 3S 2650mAh 1C
  • Charger: SkyRC iMax B6AC V2

https://www.3dhubs.com/eindhoven/hubs/cncreate/3dprint This is a customizer to create your very own planetary gearbox. Keep these principles in mind while choosing your parameters. If you don't, your gearbox will be useless. R = amount of teeth in the ring
P = amount of teeth in the planets
S = amount of teeth in the sun Equations
  • ratio = incoming speed / outgoing speed = (R + S) / S => R = (ratio - 1) * S
  • P = (R - S) / 2 = whole number
    • Use the first equation to determine R and S, do this by fixing the ratio and find the smallest combitination of R and S that fits the second equation. Keep in mind that if R is even, S should also be even, else the second equation will never be satisfied. Another important tip is that when you set the ratio too high, the planets will become to big and the sun will be too small. Also, don't make the amount of teeth on the gears much lower than 10. Example: I require a ratio of 3.5. I choose S = 10, which gives me R = 25. According to equation 2, P = 7.5, which is not allowed. I try S = 12, which gives R = 30 and P = 9, which is allowed.

This was one of the first projects I tried to tackle in 3-D design.
I used a high-resolution jpg file of my school's seal/logo/crest as the starting point, and wanted to create a 3-D printable version for our 3-D printer. I went through a process of converting the raster image to a vector image to a CAD programming language to a 3-D model, and then intended to combine these 3-D models together into a single one.
Once I got to the final step I did not know enough to succeed, and wound up putting it aside and coming back to it later when I learned more about working with solid shapes.

This is the cat that we found to put on the MakerBot Digitizer platform for the photo out to all the folks who had signed up on the mailing list.  
The Good: It's a great model for scanning because it doesn't have any occlusions. Occlusions are like the armpits of things that are there, but not always seen. This model doesn't have any of that which is great.  
The Challenge: LASER CAT is a ceramic model that has a shiny, reflective coating. When lasers hit reflective things they bounce and that makes it hard to scan. To make it non-reflective. I sprayed it down with some dry shampoo which is a powder spray that has rice starch in it. A light coating with this stuff in a well ventilated area meant that it scanned easily on the first try!
I had to scale this down a little bit in MakerBot Makerware to fit into the MakerBot Replicator 2.

title: Makerbot Fifth Gen Idler Pulley Fix

description.text:
Have your idler pulley brackets on your Makerbot Mini cracked or broken? Have you been unable to figure out how to fix them without tearing the printer apart?
This small thing will help you get your printer going again by reinforcing the cracked idler pulley bracket but you'll need a friend or a second printer to print these.

You will need:
  • Clear epoxy - use the 5-minute set type
  • 2.5mm hex wrench
  • 2mm hex wrench
  • Print (2) parts for each side you want to repair.
  • Loosen the belt tension by loosening the hex bolt on the back of the printer on the top left-hand side (as facing the printer).
  • Loosen the stepper motor set screws located in the back upper-left corner of the printer. Not the four bolts holding the stepper motor - the two located to the right.
  • Move the stepper motor forward until the belt is slack. You don't want any tension on the belt during the next step.
  • Apply a generous amount of epoxy to the inside of the part and place one on the top and one on the bottom of the bracket as shown in the photo. Note that this is very hard to see and you almost have to put your head in the printer and look up toward the front. Be careful not to get any epoxy on the idler pulley or belt. Wipe it off immediately if you do.
  • Allow the epoxy to set completely (usually overnight) then tighten the belt again. You do not need the belt so tight it plays a C# when plucked. That's way too tight! Just make it tight enough that there is still about 10-15mm of play in the belt.
    • Note: If your brackets have broken to the point of the idler pulley coming away from the bracket, your pulley brackets may be beyond the help of this thing. In that case, you will have to purchase a new set from MBI. However, installation is not obvious. If you want to install them yourself, send me a private message and I'll walk you through it. It's not difficult if you have some mechanical skill, but I do not recommend it for those who have little or no mechanical skills.

title: Model Rocket - B & C Engine Size

description.text:
UPDATE - I've added "Rocket 2 - Payload.stl" It's the same size rocket, but with a payload section at the top. It also has a new lighter weight motor retention system, made from a cleverly bent large paper clip to keep the weight down. To assemble, straighten a large standard paper clip. Bend the "U" at one end, insert downward, from the nose cone end toward the tail end. Then bend the paperclip out sideways, and add the knee bend and loop at the end. It acts like a torsion spring to retain the rocket motor. I tried unsuccessfully to properly print out the rockets that were here on thingiverse, so my son and I designed our own in solidworks. I think it was mostly due to learning the limitations of our TOM, and not a problem with the existing designs. You will notice that this is a "all at once" print, where you print the fins, tubes and nose cone all at the same time. There are connecting ribs between the parts so that the fin section will stabilize the other tall thin parts - you'll notice in one of the pictures that the print failed near the end when the tall skinny tubes were tilting around on the ABP conveyor belt.
It is currently just a simple design, but I hope to design a version that will include a mount for a "Spy-pen" camera to take video, and possibly one that will launch gliders when the nosecone is ejected, perhaps a propeller retrieval option for the nosecone - and any other wild ideas my 4 & 7 year olds come up with...
This was printed on a Thing-O-Matic, with a MK6 extruder, ABP (which made the first attempt unstable), the layer height is .35mm, feedrate of 30, and we used white ABS so the kids could color the sections with markers. Update-
I have added a STL without the connecting ribs - just make sure you have a solid foundation - the incomplete print in the pictures was because the conveyor belt on my ABP was too "floppy" when the parts got that tall.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SmgKZMTUywQ
1.) Download file & create g-code
2.) Print parts
3.) Trim away connecting "webs" - these add stability during printing
4.) Assemble - glue sections together, leave nosecone a light friction fit (sand as needed) - Paint if desired - use 2 drywall screws for the original design in opposing holes to secure the motor - use one of the remaining holes for the guide rod on the launcher. For the newer design, bend a large paperclip as shown.
5.) Launch! (if you lose/break/destroy it, repeat steps 2-5)

24/18=1.333333333 It was a tight fit at 18mm, so you should probably scale it up by 1.35 to have a little more clearance. The trick is, the 24mm motors are also 70mm long, so if you scale the whole thing up by 1.35, the motor will enter into the tube too deep. If you only scale X and Y by 1.35 and you don't scale the Z axis, it should be the same height rocket, but bigger in diameter to allow the use of the D size Ø24mm x 70mm long motor. I found the dimensions for the different motors listed here: https://www.apogeerockets.com/Rocket_Motors/Estes_Motors
Interestingly enough, if you want to try this rocket with E sized motors, Ø24mm x 95mm long, you should be able to scale all three axes by 1.35 and get a Ø24mm hole that is 95mm deep.

description.text:
This is a 7/16" thick gaming tile. I provide it in two different scales. One is 2x2 inches exactly and the other is for OpenForge which is 50mm x 50mm -- which is a tad smaller than 2x2 -- 2x2 inches is 50.8mm x 50.8mm). Please download and print the appropriate file for your system. (I use 2x2 personally). This is version 1.0 of the tile. It is use 12 copies of a single sculpted plank (which I did in Blender). I rotate the plank 180 degrees every other plank so it doesn't look too matchy. Ideally I'd have multiple sculpts of this plank for an even more natural look -- working on this for v1.1 -- coming soon. Note: the photo I am sharing of it was printed at .2 layers. I suggest .1 layers if you don't mind the extra time. Painting Tips:
Start with a base of "pure black" or a "warm black". The first two coats of this black base should be watered down so it falls all the way down between the cracks of each plank. Like the viscosity should be between normal paint and a wash. If any paint is pooling between the cracks, use a needed and/or stiff brush to sweep it out. The final coat of black would be thicker but don't work that into the cracks, and if you do, again sweep out with stiff brush. Let that dry well. Then do a heavy dry brush on of Burnt Umber (I used 2 oz. America $1). You should see the burnt umber but still see the black in the wood grain at this point. Let that dry and then do a dry brush on of Terra Cotta (Americana) or an orangish brown. It should be bewteen the Burnt Umber and Cocoa (see below) in tone. I couldn't find Terra Cotta at the craft store the other day so I mixed my own mid town. I used 1 drop of burnt umber, 1 drop of cocoa and 1 drop of "burnt orange" ($1 as well). Then finally do a super light dry dry brushing on of Americana Cocoa. ($1) -- Honey Brown also works well. And that's it. I got most of these painting tips from http://dmscraft.proboards.com/thread/2710/privy I plan on using this tile in my modular dungeon system:
http://dmscraft.proboards.com/thread/3699/jennifers-dungeon-tile-system

This is a simple linear actuator that can be used in all sorts of halloween or other holiday displays. I used a cheap yardstick for the rod with a GT2 pulley and belt system connected to a NEMA 17 stepper motor. I used this design to make a fun project for an Intel Edison Hackathon. The piranha plant movement was triggered by people sending tweets. Check out my blog to read about my other projects: http://matthewcmcmillan.blogspot.com/

description.text: This barrel extension is 4.5 inches long and all the parts press fit together. It was tested on both the CS-6 and STRYFE but should fit on other models. I Designed it to lock onto the gun the same way as the "factory" extensions. The barrel is in two pieces so the tip can be printed in orange for safety. The small round piece with the bump on it is what secures it to the gun, if it wears down or breaks it can be easily replaced/reprinted without having to reprint the whole barrel. Feel free to remix this I would love to see them. Testing with the two guns I have, this barrel definitely improves accuracy without hurting the range as much as the longer extensions do.
